Murang a town residents have asked the government to come up with alternative penalties for capital offences, saying executions violate religious teachings. They spoke on Friday at a public forum organised by the Power of Mercy Advisory Committee.They said convicts should be used to implement development projects such as road construction. Kikuyu Council of Elders member Joachim Gitonga said life is sacred and the state should use traditional means to punish convicts.But Murang a Township chief Charles Muna said the death penalty should not be scrapped as it deters many people from engaging in capital crime.